text: I view each of the Mad Max movies as a unique film. The character is the same, but the setting seems a bit different every time. For example, in the original, there's a sense that the organized society (albeit a failing one) still exists, with medical services, the police, fire department, etc, still somehow muddling through. In the intro to the Road Warrior, however, we learn in the intro sequence that the society has crumbed down due to wars over oil, and that the events in the original film were all part of that decay. A the movie progresses, however, we clearly see that the last vestiges of an organized society have all been wiped out. In Thunderdome, furthermore, for the first time there's a talk of radiation and nuclear armageddon and there's even a clearer sense of "before" and "after". Now, a franchise is rebooted, and from its trailers it looks like its' going to be a cross-over between Thunderdome and Road Warrior. However, I personally would prefer to see more of the original (1979) Mad Max world, with a semblance of a still-existing, albeit crumbling, organized society. Perhaps, the 2014 Australian movie Rover was more faithful to the original 1979 Mad Max film than the Fury Road, which obviously harks back at its sequels, will ever be.

text: I'm feeding all of the trolls but I don't mind. People are calling this Borderlands: The Movie? I guess they're unaware that George Miller has directed, written and produced 3 other Mad Max films in 1979,  1981 and 1985. All of them basically defined the post apocalyptic genre in my eyes. Fallout, Borderlands and virtually any video game that has a barren wasteland tone was probably inspired by what Miller did with the first 3 Mad Max films and of course other great post apocalyptic films. Miller didn't create the post apocalyptic genre that's been going on since before the 50s but in my opinion he just perfected it. notice how I typed "in my opinion" just in case I get firebombed.

text: From what I've been reading, a bulk of the movie is one long car chase across the desert. Most of the effects and stunts are practical, but CGI was needed for the more impossible elements.This time, Max teams up with a character called Furiosa, who's trying to get five young women, kept as breeding property by the warlord Immortan Joe, to safety. It's a simple plot, which suits the series fine. "Fury Road" isn't a reboot; think of it as just another Max Rockatansky adventure, only with Tom Hardy as the lead this time. Works for James Bond. Why not Mad Max?

text: Sorry I don't like this "Max" either. Save for lovely  Charlize Theron, I will attend this movie just because it's a "Max" movie and I'm some sort of a fan... but I still dig the first, classic one, with the real Max, Jim Goose, Fifi, "Toe Cutter", Bubba Zanetti, "interceptors", "pursuit" patrols, and a lot of Z1000 Kawasakis with "open mufflers" rolling around. Usually I'm not a purist, but I think, in this particular case, the "Mad Max" classic was untouchable, even by George Miller himself. All of this "evolution of decadence" was not exactly my thing since franchise's  part 2. And those battle on the run scenes... everybody does that in every action movie these days!

text: Theres so many reasons to love this movie, but one reason that makes me not want to see it in the theatre, NO AUSTRALIAN ACCENTS ANYWHERE! a movie originality set in Australia with Australian actors and characters. This is way too good of an example of hollywood raping movies that they have stolen from other countries AKA the 90s godzilla film.  i was really excited when i heard they were rebooting Mad max, one of the 1# movies of my child hood. Being an Australian myself, i always jump at the opportunity to see awesome movies made by Australians and seeing trailers for this movie has sickened me quite deeply, seeing a Australian franchise whos characters were identifiably Australian has now been ruined to catour to an American audience that the original movie probably wasent targeted at in the first place. Its truly unfortunate that things like this happen in the film industry, i dont know what other reason there would be to have the characters be American other then to appeal more to an American audience, all i do know is that its going to lose some Australian fans over this. I dont know why there hasent been any coverage about this on forums or on youtube and i think it should be addressed for the sake of die hard mad max fans that are bothered by this as much as I am right now.

text: For people who keep thinking this is a continuation of the original Mad Max series, it is not.  From IMDB.com "It is a reboot. At the April 30th, 2014 test screening in Burbank, CA. Director George Miller told attendees that the reason for a reboot was that too much time had passed between the last Mad Max film to do a sequel or a film set between, along with doing such would mean a plague of continuity issues and creativity restrictions. George also commented that he didn't want to do a "remake" as he had no intention on retelling a story already told. A reboot allowed him to bring the universe and wasteland 30 years up to date while keeping Max as the moviegoers remember him, a man with nothing to lose after the loss of his family".  "From Warner Bros. press release: "Mad Max: Fury Road Seminal director George Miller returns to the post-apocalyptic universe he created three decades ago with the cultural phenomenon Mad Max. Tom Hardy reinvents Max Rockatansky in Mad Max: Fury Road, Millers extraordinary new take on the legendary character for a new generation of fans."  "The storyline borrows from the setup of the original trilogy, particularly from the second movie but in its own new universe. Set years after the new Max (Tom Hardy) lost his family during the early days of the societal collapse. Max is now a lone drifter in the post-apocalyptic wasteland as an empty shell of a man with very little left to lose".

text: Mad Max 4: Fury Road is the upcoming Australian-American post-apocalyptic action film directed, produced, and co-written by George Miller, and the fourth film of Miller's Mad Max franchise. The first film of the franchise in 30 years, Fury Road stars Tom Hardy as "Mad" Max Rockatansky, making it also the first Mad Max film not to feature Mel Gibson in the title role. It also stars Charlize Theron.  The film will have its world premiere on 14 May 2015 at the 68th Cannes Film Festival in an out of competition screening, followed by a wide theatrical release on 15 May 2015.

text: Reasons for fans to be excited.  Been a fan of the series for 30 years since i saw the first 2 on video and part 3 in theaters at age 4.   Here are some reasons:   The first 2 were r-rated adult oriented gritty sci-fi action picks with style and class, part 3 was a PG-13 family film, fun with nice performance by Tina Turner if a bit watered down compared to the first 2 even it's not as bad as AVP or Robocop 3 or mediocre as Terminator Salvation.   I'm glad George Miller is back as director and they got a nice writer for this, although Mel will be missed but Hardy should be a nice replacement. I'm also glad it's back to the R-rated formula as we already had one PG-13 MM movie and that was 30 years ago as it was enough, i mean nice to see them go back to the adult oriented gritty formula of the first 2 classics. I mean we had R-rated hits recently like Kingsman, Equalizer and American Sniper proving there is an audience for these kinds of action films. Hell even Predators proved when it went back to the R-rated formula after the dismal AVP showed there can be love for an adult orienited r-rated series.   Plus some old school practical effects with new stuff mixed in and all that.

text: Just saw it here it is my review: If you are a fan of the saga go see it now, if you are not...go see it anyways! George Miller the original director returns as the father of post-apocalyptic cinema. The textures and the colours of the movie maintain the atmosphere of the old ones. The action is smart and fast. You will be on the edge of your seat all the time. The designs of the cars are original as fuck. The concept artists and the VFX artists did a great job, an amazing one. The writting is very good. You wouldnt expect such an original screenplay and dialogue from a blockbuster but thats thanks to George Miller and his writters team. The stunts are amazing they did a hell of a job with the camera movements. The characters have each one their own arch. The acting is specific to this kind of world. The world created feels like poetry. Cinematography is punk as hell. Conclusion: 5 stars. A beautiful ride.

text: I've been waiting years for a great, mind-blowing movie - and this is IT!  It is not all action, all chase like some people are saying.  However each chase on its own is incredible.   There are several sad, touching and tragic moments as well - even surprising and believable romantic moments given the amount of carnage and fear the escapees are in.  The sets and vehicles are spectacular.  The landscapes and weather are awe-inspiring.  Hats off - and chains off - to George Miller, cast and crew and makeup effects people.

text: From director George Miller, originator of the post-apocalyptic genre and mastermind behind the legendary “Mad Max” franchise, comes “Mad Max: Fury Road,” a return to the world of the Road Warrior, Max Rockatansky.  Haunted by his turbulent past, Mad Max believes the best way to survive is to wander alone. Nevertheless, he becomes swept up with a group fleeing across the Wasteland in a War Rig driven by an elite Imperator, Furiosa. They are escaping a Citadel tyrannized by the Immortan Joe, from whom something irreplaceable has been taken. Enraged, the Warlord marshals all his gangs and pursues the rebels ruthlessly in the high-octane Road War that follows. 4.75/5 read the text above here in the Publised section..... Craziness also has WITNESSES.... Charlize Theron is Mind Blowing... Mad Max Tom hardy is too MAD HARD

And George Miller did a spectacular job not making this movie feel cluttered.  Tom Hardy was amazing. Charlize Theron was a complete badass. Nicholas Holt is incredible. I can not think of ONE flaw in this movie. Terrific screenplay, the stunts were something I had never seen before. And as a huge fan of the previous Mad Max films (excluding the third), I can say that if you are considering going to see this movie, make sure you are ready for what this movie will do to you. In the most beautiful way possible.

text: I went into this with low expectations, not hearing any reviews yet or the fact that this film is generally well regarded.  Knowing only that I'm almost invariably disappointed by remakes, sequels with long layovers of films I loved back in the day, and of most films period really these days.  And I think that made the experience that much more enjoyable.  It's better than going in with high expectations and having them dashed.   It was what anyone would expect of a Mad Max movie... lot's of action and badassery.  And did what it does very, very well.  I may like it better than the original trilogy even.  Best film of 2015 thus far without doubt and one of the best action films I've seen in the past several years.  And an amazing 3D experience as well...one of the most riveting of all time.  I plan on paying to have it again.

text: People have been saying that the Avengers AOU is a better film, and I disagree. I love the marvel universe just as much as the next guy, but strictly from a cinematographic standpoint, Mad Max was far superior. Joss wheaten is a capable writer, but he is nowhere near a great visual storyteller. His shots are rather bland and not cinematically motivated. They may look "cool" because of all of the flashy cgi, but if you take them for what they are, they are nothing special. George Miller on the other hand utilized a lot of interesting film techniques in the movie. His manipulation of frame rate in the edit allowed for a unique rhythm in pacing. His use of a centered framing style helped keep the audience oriented and concentrated on the action. His use of color helped to differentiate the universe from a sea of bland desaturated post-apocalyptic wastelands in films. Miller showed a solid understanding of the craft of filmmaking and I think that is commendable. He was also able to create very entertaining and dynamic character arcs that showed lots of development (Furiosa finding out about her home, Nux's change of heart, Max's eventual willingness to help) without shoving the emotional moments down the audiences throat. He let these characters be defined by their actions, as they should be. I enjoy both films but Mad Max was a  quantifiably more artistic and cinematic. I Highly recommend checking it out!

text: Saw this movie today. Its an awesome watch and a must for action lovers. If you're expecting intricate story telling and vast references that link up previous Mad Max movies then you'll be sorely disappointed. Dont go into this film with that mindset. Mad Max was made famous for its action packed sequences with amazing stunts. This movie is exactly that, but for almost the entire film. It delivered on all fronts as far as action goes. Think of it as another epic story in the life of Max. I mean do you go around telling strangers about your past?! No you dont, and thats why I seriously put this down as one of the action greats, jumps straight into the chaos and barbarism of the Mad Max universe. I could easily watch It twice in a row and still feel excited.

Action? 9/10, repetitive at some points, but as i said, worthwhile Story? i can't rate it, considering there wasn't any story actually going on, the point of watching this movie is the visuals and action scenes. its about immortan joe, wanting to get back his female property/ or what ever they were considered to him, they escaped with furiosa and the action begins from here.  Should you watch this movie?  A- if you're into action movies, then this is perfect for you, definitely a badass movie, with many memorable scenes B-if you're into story, then you'll be disappointed Overall Rating 8/10

text: Just saw this last night, absolutely fantastic! Delivered all the machinery and the inner working guts of mechanical post apocalyptic muscle you could want without any terrible CGI overkills ruining it. So gritty and legit, distilled everything you loved about the original mad max's and amped it up with a beefier budget while not selling out. Its weird, unlike any other movies out there, and its more car chase scene that anything, but enough plot to give over 2h of absoltuely incredible vehicular mayhem chase scenes justice. Also a welcome healthy serving of gore, not toned down for the masses. Those who liked the originals for what they were will not be disappointed.

text: The reason why I hope this movie dose well it would force companies to balance between practical effects and props and CGI and they could make vast amounts of money. And this movie felt even more balanced with male and female heroes. A few younger folk say the movie lacked dialog but idk this type of movie was always focused more on action. To me this feels like a more mature version of Mad Max but that may just be me. I compare the Movie The Empire Strikes Back-though at the time not as much CGI was possible, but I use that movie to judge on the full balance of humor, set pieces ect. That movie, just like Fury Road has the right feel it needs.What I mean is its fantasy but it dosen't feel cartoony. I think adults will be pleased. It's been a long time since we seen anything like this before. I hope classic horror will make a return as well. Horror as art not torture porn.

text: There come times in movie history where a genre defining film is created, something so magnificent and grand that it forever affects the films of the future. Mad Max: Fury Road is a film that your grandchildren will ask if you saw it in theaters, and those of us who did will be proud to tell our children "yes." The movie begins with picking the audience up and placing them in the universe of Mad Max: where packs of roving guzzoline seeking bandits and psychopaths dwell, killing all who oppose them, and where two headed, irradiated lizards are eaten raw without a second thought. The sheer deadness of the world is gorgeous, and the fact that they use very little CGI brings it home. When the audience sees the stunts, cars flipping, exploding, stuntmen being thrown from them as they careen into canyon walls, they see real people and vehicles. Too often has a overly digital set and stunts made an action movie a sterile pool of disgusting brackish water, and bland characters who are either immortal or unlikable only add to it. Yet, Mad Max is the opposite: Max and Furiosa are very mortal, and their peril is real. Max is strapped to the front of a car and driven around the desert while being used as a blood bag, and Furiosa comes quite near death on several occasions. The enemies are made human by the addition of Nux, a War Boy who joins the protagonists, and only serves the Big Bad due to a religious devotion instilled in him by brainwashing. The Five Wives are very human, and compelling, given varied personalities. The movie, despite being an action packed thrill ride, makes time for subtle character development along the way. And this movie is truly a nonstop action scene. Perhaps fifteen minutes of its almost two hour stretch were slow, and its constant adrenaline rush makes one near mad. Every single bit of it is George Miller's genius, and it is truly unusual in the times of shallow plots and characters in action, where stunts are fake and blows softened by the cutting of a camera. Watch this movie.

text: This Mad Max movie, even though  directed by George Miller,  MUST be a separate entity or an alternate story from the other Mad Max films as it would not make any sense if it took place anytime during the first 3 Mad Max films.  In the beginning of Fury Road, we see Max driving his Interceptor which where he then crashes and gets captured. But how could this be?  His Interceptor was blown up in Mad Max 2/ The Road Warrior. This could not of taken place before the Road Warrior because Max would not have had his car anymore since it was crashed in Fury Road..  In Thunderdome, he was an older character and would not made any sense, plus his Interceptor was long gone when Thunderdome came along with him riding a camel pulled vehicle.  Fury Road seems to be an alternate story to the Road Warrior as it would have been at the same timeline with Mad Max's character being at the approximate same age and driving his Interceptor out in the desert wasteland, but they could not have happened in the same universe unless Max found the exact same Interceptor that was destroyed in both films,

text: I'm not usually one for dystopian films but everything in the trailers was so amazing I had to go and see if with my boyfriend. Both of us loved it from beginning to end. Over 80% of the movie is real action and not CGI (which was mostly removed to erase wires, for Charlize's arm, etc.) so there were guys on moving vehicles at high speed doing acrobatics and shit for real which is terrifying and amazing!  Some people complained about how Max didn't appear to be the central character despite being titular. Max has always been more of a narrative voice. He's the guy who walks into someone else's story and has a part to play in it, but it's never all about him. He's our eyes and ears in this other world.  ~SPOILER WARNING~  And this was about so much more than 'The Wives'. It was about a war lord suppressing the people he was meant to be in charge of. Preventing them from getting the basic natural requirements to life like food and water. Keeping the plant life high above their reach and living above them as if he was somehow closer to the Gods. Promising them salvation and a place in Valhalla for serving him, which are things no man has control over. Exploiting their desperation for a better world to incite their loyalty.  So if you want to see the best action film of this year, with real character development (Nux, Furiosa, The Wives, Max) as their co-dependency evolves from a need to survive to genuine compassion for one another's well-being, exceptional stunts, villains who are oddly reminiscent of today's politicians in parts, and people who stand as equals regardless of their appearance, health, gender, and capabilities, then you HAVE to watch this movie.

text: One of the worst movies I've ever seen, although Charlize Theron was pretty good in it. Hell, it was pretty much her movie with Tom Hardy as a supporting cast member. The car chases were fun as always but we've seen it all before in the previous Mad Max movies. OK, the porcupine cars were unique to the series but that s about it. I was half expecting to see a helicopter of some kind join the chase, it was that generic.  Other reasons why was it so bad?  1. Ultra lame plot. What did it take Miller to come up with that? 5 seconds?   2. Tom Hardy is NOT Mad Max. Not even close. Not even for a single second did I think of him as Max. He did remind me a bit of of Harrison Ford in "Force 10 From Navarone". And if they ever did a movie about Han Solo's early years, he might be good in that role.  3. Lots of dumb\sloppy stuff. For example, the pass is blocked by a massive landslide and then, as if by magic, all of the rocks are removed on the return trip. Or the guy with the spot light randomly shooting in the dark despite having no clue how far ahead they were. Or hooking the trucks winch up to the dead tree and Max helps hold the tree up!!! Or Theron helping push the rig when it was stuck in the mud! HAHAHAHAAHHAAHHA!!!   The main good thing about the movie is Miller wisely staying away from too much CGI effects.Other than that, there's not much left to praise. Gibson was truly wise to stay clear of this stinker of a movie.

text: No-spoiler: really lame CGI in the final shot of the film, some lame CGI flames.  The rest? The best, unapologetic action movie I have seen since Shoot 'Em Up, Kickass or the other Mad Max Movies.  Or Terminator 1 and 2.  The characters made sense, everything in the movie was justified, even people huffing paint and swinging on poles to attack other people in cars, and every over-the-top element fit into this show perfectly. Any person involved in film making can learn from George Miller.  Thank goodness you exist, thank you for doing four great films.  Thank you.   #GeorgeMiller

text: Can't wait until this movie comes out on bluray. It addresses some really relevant issues: bodily autonomy, PTSD, regaining humanity, the harms of capitalism, the world when all the resources are controlled by the few, and as a result, how everyone becomes dependent on the top out of sheer necessity only to be condemned for that dependence. It also covers what happens when the youth is raised to blindingly follow an ideal or figure so that they become willing and disposable cannon fodder for the powerful. And best of all, the whole movie is a fight for humanity with very little CGI, so people literally risked their lives to make this movie.

text: Beeing a fan of the Mad Max movies, and seeing how this movie was getting such good critics, I was looking forward to this movie. But now words cannot describe how dissapointed I am. This actually might be THE movie, the movie that makes me stop watching movies. Atleast for a while, I need to catch some breath. It is so stupid and superficial, I don't even know how to explain, thats how dumb it is. If I wanted to see stunts I'd go to a stunt show, I watch a movie to be entertained or touched, not bored. I give this movie a 2 out of 10. The visuals easily make this movie a 7 or 8, but I have to retract points because the story line is very bad. I can't believe how bad the story is in this movie and solely relies on visuals, there were plenty of moments I was grossed out by all the cheesiness. Thanks for ruining mad max, but atleast mass hype works and hollywood earned lots of money.

text: My list for best movies of 2015 so far... 1. Mad Max: Fury Road- best Mad Max movie I've ever seen...well that's because I haven't seen the other movies. Tom Hardy and Charlize Theron are badass in this movie. If this movie wins any award, I will be shouting "OH WHAT A DAY! WHAT A LOVELY DAY!!!" 2. Jurassic World- now that's a worthy sequel. You really can't compare it to the original series, because it basically ignores the other sequels. Even if it can't beat the original, it was fun and awesome. Chris Pratt and Bryce Dallas Howard were great. Awesome ending btw. 3. Inside Out- such an original and heartfelt movie that should be watched by plenty. It has superb animation (as always from Pixar), likable characters (Bing Bong is my favorite), and it has such creative writing. Thank you Pixar for not being disappointing like your Cars movies. Pixar is back on track. 4. Avengers: Age of Ultron- I thought it was good, but I still think Guardians of the Galaxy is the best MCU movie (MY OPINION!!!). Ultron was a cool villain, and I love the addition to Quicksilver and Scarlet Witch. If there's one problem, I wish it was darker and less repetitive. Still good none the less.

text: The action is bad ass, but there are few issues with the character build up  ...  Building character sympathy toward mad max fell from the beginning when he first  left them behind and tried to run on his own.  since then I personally  hated madmax till the end of the movie ,,  unlike the old mill Gibson character. 2nd point is for the bad leader with the mask, as much as we and  the director  try to paint an ugly picture to hate this evil dude, if you look at it, he was only  chasing after his child (property). and notice he was trying to save the girl who mad max shot in the leg in the first place which cased her to fell and die. Another point is why were the girls running , i mean they could deliver the child and then run, they had luxury life, but notice they wanted hope (similar to the obama hope), meaning when we imagine hope universally ,  notice they broke free from the underwear with spikes... in other words this evil lord had brides that he didn't want them to sleep with other men, then placed a spiked underwear that they broke free from that was part of their hope. This is exactly the mindset of the U.S. forging policy. when they invaded Iraq mr Bush was worried about women in Iraq that couldn't vote :( so sad !!! Going back to the point , the film generated a negative sense of sympathy toward mad max, and although the evil lord looked as ugly as he did, at least some empathy was built toward he movie since he wanted to save his child and get him back... this was not intentional .. just my thoughts .

text: I don't know if it's been said but to me Warhammer 40k (especially the orc race) was clearly an inspiration for costuming, vehicles and culture for this movie. The "War Rig" looks like it came straight from the "WHAAAAGGGHHH!!" factory LOL!  And, Important Joe looks like a freaking TECH PRIEST or Assassin. I love WH40K and loved the imagery that parallels  it in this movie; especially, the mash-up of humans living in a warrior based society based solely on survival through brute strength, superiority and pecking order without reason and with pure aggression... aka acting like orcs. I Have never seen anyone put the two concepts together and it worked incredibly well. Absolutely creative and beautiful cinematography and imagery.   The only negative point I have to say about the movie is it was more Furiosa based with minimal dialogue and we learned absolutely nothing new about Mad Max, whom I believe probably had less than 50 lines and most of them were grunts and "no"... lol

text: You know that scene right after the storm where Max drives off with the truck leaving everyone behind? Well though I have nothing against that scene that is where I would draw a line on the ground to divide the good from the not so good. Even though I think the robot arm was a bit too sci-fi for Mad Max and the guy with the guitar was a bit cheesy I was still over 90% positive about the film until that point. But once it gets passed that driving off scene which I have described there then really does seem to be a sudden decline in quality. The dialogue wasn't very interesting and the action seemed to be an extremely watered down version of what occurred in the first quarter of the film. So I'm not complaining that they were recycling material. I'm complaining that it was watered down recycled material that just seemed boring in comparison to the first quarter.

text: I can't believe the number of people who have the audacity to be so inattentive and ignorant when complaining about this movie. It's inexcusable, and it's turning a lot of people off from this masterpiece, so I'm going to deconstruct all of their incorrect arguments for those who haven't seen:  "There's no story and dialog/terrible story." Sure, there's very little dialog and exposition, but that does not mean there is no story. Mad Max: Fury Road excels in visual storytelling, a unique and interesting form of storytelling which very few big budget Hollywood titles use. If you think there is no story, you simply aren't paying attention to the movie. While the overall story is fairly basic and predictable, the amount of depth put into the situations and the way they are woven together, as well as small details throughout the movie and references to Miller's other work, is so masterfully done that it overshadows all of this. Besides, a movie does not NEED to be complex to be good. I've seen the movie 3 times now and each time I notice a new detail I had never noticed before.  "It's all just one long action segment/car chase." ... And? Isn't that what you pay for when you go to an action film? Isn't that why the name of the genre is "ACTION"? Take a look at the latest Fantastic Four, it did the exact opposite of Mad Max in terms of plot, backstory, narrative and build-up vs. pure, raw, exciting, intense action, and look at the difference in response between them. It's also masterfully directed, using a tracking technique where the action is always being followed precisely between shots. This was covered in the Mad Max Film Theory Video if you're interested in this technique, as it really makes the film much better than all the shitty action segments Michael Bay puts out.  "It's feminist propaganda." This is false. The want to free from oppression and sexual slavery from a brutal, oppressive dictator, as well as the idea of women being diverse, in terms of beauty, skills and character, and capable of being on the same level as men, is not exclusive to feminism. Really, it's an idea that all human beings who aren't scumbags should embrace.  "The film is full of CGI."/"The film is boring."/"(Other Strange Generic Argument from someone with Insanity or a Meth Pipe)." What are you talking about? Did you even watch the same movie? Did you too, like the people who say it has no story, just not even look at the screen for more than 5 seconds before declaring you were bored? Did you forget to take your ADHD meds today?  Alright, rant over. Seriously, this movie is one of the best action movies of all time. There's a reason it's being praised by everyone who has any sort of sense of what makes a movie good. it's incredibly entertaining and brilliant, unique yet familiar, and you need to watch it considering those points above.

text: This film shows how you can tell a story and develope great charakters without having two hours of pure dialogue. I mean, look at Charlize Theron's face at 0:48. She doesn't need to say: "You took everything from me and turned me into the right hand of a tyrant. Now I'll take whats most precious to you, and if it's the last thing I'll ever do." One shot of her face is enough to say all of that. Or take that blone girl at 1:03 leaning out of the car. In every other movie she'd have said something like: "If you want me back, you'll have to kill me. Me and your son, because I'll not be a slave anymore, and my son will not be a warlord.". All It took was one second of her face. Even though this movie is kind of short on plot, this way of telling the story is genius.

text: BEST movie I have seen for ages!! Fucking loved it!!! Completely blew me away, way surpassed my expectations!!!  It's so rare that a sequel doesn't suck... this did total justice... it was like 15 years in the making.    I read that it was going to be filmed on location in Australia but there was rain which caused a lot of flowers to grow and would have ruined the post-apocalyptic vibe, so they moved it to the Namibian Desert which is AMAZING, that red dirt like being on Mars...... final word, hats of to the stunt team, the stunts and mutant vehicles are absolutely incredible.      Also even though it's obviously an action movie there were some interesting subtleties of concept woven in.... both male and female heroes who are both badass, the fact that she has lost an arm is an amazing touch of humanity, also the antipatriarchal sentiment, even a hint of Stockholm syndrome.

The only female "warboy", I had to look on a wiki page for some answers, seems the spend all the budget on cgi action and couldn't be bothered to explain anything. I don't think it's a bad movie, just not as good as Road Warrior and Hardy isn't anywhere near as good as Mel Gibson's Max.

text: Great action sequences, but pretty mindless and nonsensical. First of all, this is supposed to be the apocalyptic future where water and gas are scarce. You would think that there would be a lot less driving if gas was scarce. But in this movie, people are driving endlessly, wasting lots and lots of gas.   This is like a future fueled by drug hallucinations and physical survival skills. This is where the movie excels.  When I saw those beautiful girls with Charlize Theron, I cringed. They look like fashion models. This movie is like a GQ photoshoot on steroids. Gorgeous to look at and fun to watch and rewatch. But I still think Mad Max 2 (The Road Warrior) is the best.  Tom Hardy is hardly in the movie. This is basically a Charlize Theron movie.

text: Not my kind of movie,so to my surprise, I fucking LOVED IT!!!....Amazing action sequences,but surprisingly it drew me in emotionally to characters that I originally didn't even care for,like Nux(war boy). When he failed suicide TWICE,was funny. But the 3rd time he says,"witness me", and flips the car over to save the girls,broke my heart and made my eyes tear up!...Also,when they snatched Zoe Kravitz's character(forgot her name)from the car and you see her kicking and screaming and Furiousa screams "NOOOO!",  Uggh my heart sank just like when Splendid died so tragically and unexpectedly...I  felt HORRIBLE when Furiosa, after traveling so far, realized she had gone the OPPOSITE direction! Man, the look on her face just said it all. I really felt her desperation...And last one lol, in the beginning when Max is caged up in the front of the car, I just kept saying, "Omg that SUCKS so bad!!!!" lol I would've died if that was me!.. Sorry I just had to get all that outta my system....Hope I wasn't the only one that felt that way! If so, Oh fucking well lol.

text: Sorry but comparing this to the 3 previous Mad Max movies, this was a real let down in so many levels. Max in the last 3 movies was a road warrior,  in MAD MAX he took out the bikers for killing his wife and child as sweet revenge introducing the V8 Interceptor, MAD MAX 2 the road warrior in search for fuel helps a community relocate from scavengers. MAD MAX beyond thunderdome, takes max into a city of violence, outcast from Aunty finds a lost tribe who he helps find the old world. This Fury Road comes down to a bunch of woman saving his ass from being killed, the main woman seems to have more balls than Max. The character choice to play Max was all wrong, and failed to deliver on Max true story. It was a movie based on one big chase, with clean looking cars instead of rusty old welded machines. I'm sorry but this is my opinion and as a collector of Mad Max memorabilia, knowing the movies word for word and a movie buff of the 3 trilogy films, and watching these films since 1980 this Fury Road was all wrong.

text: Not only one of the best action flicks ever made, one of the BEST movies ever made all-around. Absolutely stunning with no flaws, IMO. Each and every character has a fully-realized story arc - not just Nux and Furiosa, but Max as well. To all critics saying the titular character was underdeveloped... just remember, he was the reluctant hero trying to survive when he realized by the end that he couldn't just walk away from a noble cause again. Not until his mission was complete. He began the film as a 'feral' reduced to being someone's blood bag... and ended it by rediscovering a part of himself lost along with the rest of the world he knew: a sense of empathy for others, a basic quality of humanity. If that isn't character development, please explain why!  I LOVE THIS FILM!

text: Why is Max always the only one who seems to have a strong connection to the old civilization? Like, he is the only one who remembers it clearly, he is the only one who seems to have a civilized demeanour and does NOT (paradoxically enough) seem mad at all. I mean, litterally everyone else seem to be inbred weirdos who've been handed down stories over generations regarding the old world. Its always like Max is from a completely different era and really doesnt fit into that whole setting, he is way too old worldish. Some people claim that its because Max is old and that its a generational issue... but look at him! Old? Hell, there are older characters in the movies who act just as bonkers as everyone else. This has always been a point of conflict with me, even though I adore the movies.

text: The film was a blunder, it really was not about Mad Max and the characters were weak within the context of their character roles. It was more about the Imperator Furiosa, played by Charlize Theron than the main character played by Tom Hardy. The original 1979 miller version was way better than this film, and Mad max's dead daughter haunting him throughout the film; was just creepy! I was surprised how Miller failed this film.Nevermind that in the original film Mad Max, was originally a police officer, fighting to maintain law and order in a nuclear apocalyptic Australia. Its storyline was weak, because it lacked story context, and lacked in introducing the characters into the film. It also lacked the vivational sensation of an action packed film, which was pretty with the CPG; which is the only thumbs up it will get from me. The only thing I hope is that when they come out with Mad Max wasteland; that Miller learned his lesson. I hope it is way better than fury road because if not it will be the death of Millers franchise. Mad Max Wasteland was set to be released in 2017. However, there was a law suite by Miller against Warner brothers that has delayed the films release date.

text: The best part about this movie is all the little things in it. This movie is the epitome of show don't tell. Which is best shown with Immortan Joe. We are never told that his health is failing, we are never told he was a soldier before the fall, we are never told he is a vain egotist. All of that is shown in his introduction. His boil covered skin, the plexiglass armor designed to make him look physically fit, and the breathing apparatus all show us that his health is failing but he still seeks to appear strong and fit. And his power and greed is also shown in the movie. In a world where most have nothing he had two of everything. He possessed two chrome revolvers, and his vehicle the Gigahorse was made from two Cadillacs fused together. And unlike the rest of his fleet there's not a single spec of rust on his car. Only the people eater possessed cars as fine as the Gigahorse.

text: Sort of OK film, but no where near the scores it got on review sites. A few interesting action scenes but world building sucks harder than a porn star. And when someone makes a film in an alternate world, world building is essential. And those OK action scenes were nothing so spectacular or breathtaking, just a bunch of scenes you'd expect from Michael Bay, lots of boom boom, that's it. How did the film get 97% critic and 81-85% viewer score, I have absolutely no idea. A mediocre stupid fun if you don't have better things to do, so hard 6 at best.   As for the actors, of 3 that you will notice in the film, Tom Hardy plays Tom Hardy in torn up clothes, Charlize Theron is bland and generic with only Nicholas Hoult delivering a somewhat interesting character. The rest are basically just extras.   If there is ANYTHING that you WANT to watch besides this, go watch it, skip this one. Return to it only if there is nothing else, you are bored and you want some very stupid fun action. Even if you want very stupid fun action NOW, go find some better ones for it, there are plenty. Leave this one at the bottom of the "watchable" barrel.

I hope Miller gives us a crazy cool prequel to Fury Road or perhaps a prequel to Max first be coming a cop or a true sequel to The Road Warrior.  To those international fans wh9 live the original, you'll be spewing to know her in Victoria I live just an hour away from a few of the locations like Halls Of Justice, and the Halls Of Justice car park that was The underground car park at Melbourne university.
